
<article>
  <h3 class="mt-5">Create Multiple Pages</h3>
  <p class="w-75">Type in Terminal...</p>

<pre class="bg-light px-3"><code><span class="badge badge-secondary float-right mt-2">TERMINAL</span>
$ rails g controller pages home product pricing

</code></pre>

<p class="w-75">It should have generated <code>app/controllers/pages_controller.rb</code> with the 3 'actions' we specified.</p>
<pre class="bg-light px-3"><code><span class="badge badge-secondary float-right mt-2">CODE EDITOR</span>
<span class="block">class</span> PagesController < ApplicationController
  <span class="block">def</span> home
  <span class="block">end</span>

  <span class="block">def</span> product
  <span class="block">end</span>

  <span class="block">def</span> pricing
  <span class="block">end</span>
<span class="block">end</span>

</code></pre>

<p class="w-75">It should have also generated their corresponding 'view', or pages.
  Notice that the pages match the action names and the folder matches the controller name.
  This is done on purpose because Rails automatically associates them.</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>app/views/pages/home.html.erb</code></li>
  <li><code>app/views/pages/product.html.erb</code></li>
  <li><code>app/views/pages/pricing.html.erb</code></li>
</ul>
</article>


<article>
  <h3 class="mt-5">Set a Home Page</h3>
  <p class="w-75">Open and edit <code>config/routes.rb</code></p>

<pre class="bg-light px-3"><code><span class="badge badge-secondary float-right mt-2">CODE EDITOR</span>
Rails.application.routes.draw <span class="block">do</span>

  <span class="comment"># Set Root Path</span>
  <span class="method">root</span> 'pages#home'

<span class="block">end</span>

</code></pre>
<p class="w-75">This tells Rails that it can find the root page by going to the
  <code>PagesController</code> and the <code>home</code> action,
  which we know directs Rails to <code>pages/home.html.erb</code></p>
</article>


